## Common Mistakes

❌ Traversing only once.

The last elements cannot find greater elements at the beginning of the array.

---

❌ Forgetting to use modulo.

```java
nums[i]
```

Incorrect when `i >= n`.

Always use:

```java
nums[i % n]
```

---

❌ Storing answers during the first traversal.

Answers should only be stored during the **second traversal**.

```java
if (i < n)
```

---

## Takeaway

The key idea is to combine a **Monotonic Decreasing Stack** with **two traversals** to simulate a circular array. By using `i % n` for indexing and processing the array twice, every element gets a chance to find its next greater element, resulting in an efficient **O(n)** solution.
